## Decision tree

IF task adds a new play or set of tasks:
  → One play per logical concern — do not mix unrelated roles in one play
  → Tag every task: at minimum `[<feature>, <layer>]` e.g. `[nginx, config]`
  → If logic will be used by >1 playbook → move to a role
  → Pattern anchor: `playbook.yml`

IF task involves a new role:
  READ .ai-harness/architecture/ROLE-CONVENTIONS.md
  → Create `roles/<role-name>/` with standard layout
  → Entry point: `tasks/main.yml` — use `import_tasks:` for subtask files, `include_tasks:` only when dynamic inclusion is required
  → All variables declared in `defaults/main.yml` (overridable)
  → Role-internal constants only in `vars/main.yml`
  → Document every variable in `README.md`
  → Single responsibility: one feature per role
  → Pattern anchor: `roles/<existing-role>/`

IF task involves variables or secrets:
  READ .ai-harness/architecture/VARIABLES.md
  → vars/vault split pattern (mandatory):
    - `group_vars/<group>/vars.yml`: `db_password: "{{ vault_db_password }}"`  ← plaintext name, greppable
    - `group_vars/<group>/vault.yml`: `vault_db_password: actual_secret`        ← encrypted value
  → Prefix all vault values with `vault_`: `vault_<variable_name>`
  → Never define the same variable in both `defaults/main.yml` and `group_vars/` — pick one
  → Variable precedence (simplified): `-e` extra vars > `set_fact` > task vars > role vars > `vars_files` > `vars_prompt` > play vars > `host_vars` > `group_vars` > inventory > role defaults
  → Conditionals: `when: ansible_facts['os_family'] == "Debian"` — no `{{ }}` in `when:`

IF task involves secrets or credentials:
  READ .ai-harness/architecture/SECRETS.md
  → Encrypt with: `ansible-vault encrypt_string` (inline) or `ansible-vault encrypt vault.yml` (file)
  → Edit vault files with: `ansible-vault edit vault.yml` — never decrypt → edit → re-encrypt
  → Multi-environment: use vault identity list in ansible.cfg, encrypt per identity
  → CI/CD: vault password from CI secret store — never committed to repo
  → `.vault_pass` and `*.vault_pass` must be in `.gitignore`

IF task needs to handle command output or non-idempotent operations:
  READ .ai-harness/architecture/ERROR-HANDLING.md
  → `changed_when: "'Updated' in result.stdout"` — control changed status for shell/command
  → `failed_when: result.rc != 0 and 'already exists' not in result.stderr"` — redefine failure
  → `ignore_errors: true` — only with a documented comment explaining why
  → `block:` / `rescue:` / `always:` — for try/catch/finally patterns
  → `meta: flush_handlers` — when a later task depends on a handler having already run

IF task involves service reload or restart:
  READ .ai-harness/architecture/HANDLERS.md
  → Use handlers for: service restarts, config reloads, daemon-reload
  → Notify from the task that changes config: `notify: Restart nginx`
  → Handler name must match notify string exactly (case and whitespace)
  → Handlers run once at end of play — use `meta: flush_handlers` if mid-play execution needed
  → `listen:` pattern for multiple handlers sharing one trigger

IF task involves adding a new environment:
  READ .ai-harness/architecture/INVENTORY.md
  → Convert `inventory` file to `inventories/<env>/hosts`
  → Separate `group_vars/` per environment under `inventories/<env>/group_vars/`
  → Shared vars: `inventories/<env>/group_vars/all/vars.yml`
  → Update ansible.cfg or pass `-i inventories/<env>/` at runtime
  → Use separate vault identity per environment

IF task uses external roles or collections:
  → Add to `requirements.yml` with pinned versions — never `version: latest`
  → Install with: `ansible-galaxy install -r requirements.yml --force`
  → `collections/` is gitignored — always install from `requirements.yml`
  → Three main namespaces: `ansible.builtin.*`, `ansible.posix.*`, `community.general.*`

IF task is a fleet operation (rolling update, production change):
  → `serial: "20%"` or `serial: 1` for controlled rollout
  → `any_errors_fatal: true` for all-or-nothing operations
  → `max_fail_percentage: 10` for tolerated failure rate
  → `--limit <group>` to scope to a subset before full fleet

